{
  "set": "attribution_ref",
  "schema_version": "attribution_ref/v1",
  "description": "Edge-agnostic attribution evidence envelope over the same substrate as composite_trust_query_lite_v1 (RFC 8785 JCS + SHA-256, pin urn:x402:canonicalisation:jcs-rfc8785-v1). attribution_ref = \"sha256:\" + SHA-256(JCS({edge, subject_refs, tier})). The edge is a parameter of the shape: each edge declares its subject sequence (typed positions), its closed tier domain, and which tiers bind an observation. subject_refs is an ordered array of typed members {type, value[, observed_at_ms, observation]}; order, membership, member types and member bytes are all byte-load-bearing, so every value form is pinned: the endpoint profile is https-only with lowercase host, no port, no fragment, no userinfo (path/query byte-exact as probed); eip155 addresses are CAIP-10 with EIP-55 checksum normative on the emitter (runners enforce shape; checksum verification needs keccak-256, outside the stdlib runner envelope); did:web hosts are lowercase; member strings must be well-formed Unicode; observed_at_ms is an integer in (0, 2^53-1] so every parser sees the same value; a member carries exactly {type,value} or exactly {type,value,observed_at_ms,observation} and nothing else. Verifiers consuming claims off the wire MUST additionally require JCS-form input (re-canonicalise and byte-compare before hashing) \u2014 a JSON parser erases number form, and that gate is what makes the grammar identical across languages. Network-state rungs (signed_endpoint_claim, signed_wallet_claim on x402:payto-operator/v1) MUST bind the probe into the preimage: observed_at_ms plus a sha256 over the exact 402 response-body bytes observed. Endpoint drift then yields a legitimately different reference (po-001 vs po-003), while an altered claim over the same observation cannot keep its reference (po-neg-obs-tamper). Chain-state edges (x402:facilitator-settlement/v1) bind no observation. A tier outside the edge's domain, an observation where the edge forbids or lacks it, a reordered, dropped, duplicated or decorated subject, a non-canonical value spelling, or an unknown edge is rejected, not hashed.",
